<seg id=1> Most HKnese Not Willing to Regard Themselves as Chinese </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (FNA news from HK)Despite of the returning of HK to China last year, most HKnese were still not willing to regard themselves as Chinese, as a public poll statistics showed. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Among the 6500 thousand of the populaiton in HK, 40% called themselves "HKnese", 22.3% called themselves "HK Chinese" and 20.6% called themselves "Chinese living in HK", showed by the popular poll </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> made by the Social Science Research Center of Hong Kong University. </seg>
<seg id=5> Only 20.6% of the 517 people inquiried thought they were Chinese and other 1.6% didn't give a certain answer or made no comments. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> In similar investigations carried out half year after the returning of HK, 35.9% of the population called themselves "HKnese" and 18% regarded themselves as Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> It has been 15 months since the returning of HK and HK government is trying to remind HK residents of their Chinese nationality. </seg>
<seg id=8> HK Officials condemned the 150 years of British colonism for the embarressment it left to  HK residents on the question of their identity. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> I feel honoured as a Chinese and i am very proud of my country's development, said the Senior Officer of the HK SAR Dong Jianhua in the National Day address the day before, </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> The HK Civiliian Education Promotion Commitee published an illustrated book "I AM A CHINESE"  to help HK residents be accustomed to being Chinese citizens. </seg>
</p>
